      name: 'Russell\'s Circumplex Model',
      origin: 'James Russell, PhD (1980)',
      shortDesc: 'Emotions plotted on two axes: valence (pleasant vs. unpleasant) and arousal (high vs. low). Creates a 2D grid where any emotional state can be located. Excited = high arousal pleasant; sad = low arousal unpleasant; calm = low arousal pleasant; angry = high arousal unpleasant.',
      comparedToZones: 'Adds a second dimension (valence) that Zones doesn\'t make explicit. Yellow in Zones lumps excited (pleasant) and anxious (unpleasant) together; Circumplex separates them. More research-grounded than Zones but less child-accessible.',
      whenToUse: 'For middle and high school students who need more dimensional thinking. As a teaching tool for school psychologists explaining mood states. As basis for the Yale Mood Meter (which builds on it).',
      research: 'Russell (1980) A circumplex model of affect; Posner, Russell & Peterson on neural correlates; Yik et al. on cross-cultural application.'
